<h2>When YTD Figures Don't Add Up</h2>

<p>Occasionally your YTD figures won't match what you expect from simple multiplication. Legitimate reasons this can happen:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>You started mid-year:</strong> If you joined in May, your YTD reflects only the pay periods since you started.</li>
  <li><strong>A pay period was irregular:</strong> Short pay period at year-start/end, a one-time adjustment, a bonus paid in a separate period.</li>
  <li><strong>Mid-year rate change:</strong> If you got a raise, your YTD doesn't divide evenly by the current period rate because earlier periods used the old rate.</li>
  <li><strong>Supplemental payment:</strong> A bonus processed separately from regular payroll appears in YTD but not as a regular period multiple.</li>
</ul>

<p>If YTD figures look genuinely wrong — not explainable by any of the above — contact payroll. Errors in YTD compound: a wrong YTD federal tax number affects your W-2, which flows into your tax return.</p>

<p>YTD is also your first line of defense when your W-2 arrives in January. Your December stub's YTD figures should closely mirror the W-2 boxes. Any significant discrepancy between your final December stub and your W-2 is a payroll error to investigate before filing your taxes.</p>

